What is Digital Image Processing

  • For a given input image we do something in the middle which will have effect on the input and than get an output image. Which hopefully is what we wanted.
  • E.g. a X-ray scan which we invert all the pixel to make it more human readable

Image taken from Amira Elnouty in 01.1 - Intro & logistics slide


  • Do not mix the different image related operations

  • We manly make use of the Image Processing many. The other ones you might see a little bit.



Why Digital Image Processing

  • Processing of image data for storage, transmission
  • Image inpainting (e.g. photoshopping someone out of the picture)
  • Contrast enhancement
  • For further analysis (e.g. making a X-ray more clear to read with human eyes)



What is Digital Image

  • A digital image is a 2D array or 2D matrix
  • The matrix or array contain a finite set of pixels


Image Characteristics

  • Image size
  • The number of pixels in an image
  • Bit depth
  • The number of bits that represents the Pixels' color values
  • Bit dept-RGB image
  • A Bit depth of the colors red, green and blue added on top of each other


Image taken from Amira Elnouty in 01.1 - Intro & logistics slide


Point processing

  • The output value at a specific coordinate is dependent only on the input value at that same coordinate in the input image
  • With point processing we can do basic operations:
  • Original = inPixel
  • Darken = inPixel- x
  • Lower Contrast = inPixel/ x
  • Invert = maxNumber - inPixel
  • Lighten = inPixel + x
  • Raise Contrast = inPixel * x

Where x can be any number

  • What to do with numbers below zero and above the maxNumber?
  • You can cut it of and set it to zero or the maxNumber
  • Refactor all the pixels
  • Be creative

RGB Color model

  • RGB model uses the primary colors Red, Green and Blue to produce a color
  • The spectral components of red, green and blue are added

HSI Color model

HSI is suitable for describing the colors in the RGB cube

  • Hue: describes a pure color
  • Saturation: amount of dilution by achromatic light
  • Intensity: brightness
